# Read in exposures from CNS signature fitting and tibble it up, including the "unknown" weight
raw_exposures <- readr::read_rds(fitted_file)
decon_weights <- lapply(raw_exposures, "[[", "weights")
exposures_wide <- do.call(rbind, decon_weights) %>%
  tibble::rownames_to_column("Kids_First_Biospecimen_ID") %>%
  tibble::as_tibble() 

unknown_weights <- lapply(raw_exposures, "[[", "unknown")
unknown_weights_array <- do.call(rbind, unknown_weights)
exposures <- exposures_wide %>%
  # use "Other" for unknown
  dplyr::mutate(Other = unknown_weights_array[,1]) %>%
  # key is column name in signature_names_df
  tidyr::gather(-Kids_First_Biospecimen_ID, key = "cns_names", value = "exposure")

# Join input dataframes together
results_df <- exposures %>% 
  # Merge with metadata
  dplyr::inner_join(
    meta %>%
      dplyr::select(Kids_First_Biospecimen_ID, broad_histology, cancer_group, tumor_descriptor)
  ) %>%
  # Grab the cancer group DISPLAY specifically (needed for joining later)
  dplyr::inner_join(
      dplyr::select(palette_df, cancer_group, cancer_group_display)
  ) %>%
  # no longer need cancer_group
  dplyr::select(-cancer_group) %>%
  # Retain only cancer groups for these visualizations
  dplyr::filter(cancer_group_display %in% cancer_groups_to_plot) %>%
  # Merge with correct signal names (already factored and ordered)
  dplyr::inner_join(signature_names_df)  %>%
  dplyr::select(-cns_names) # remove signature column 
Joining, by = "Kids_First_Biospecimen_ID"
Joining, by = "cancer_group"
Joining, by = "cns_names"
# We need to create a new scheme for labeling that shows wrapped cancer groups with `(n=X)`
results_df <- results_df %>%
  dplyr::count(cancer_group_display, signature) %>%
  dplyr::select(-signature) %>%
  dplyr::distinct() %>%
  dplyr::inner_join(
      dplyr::select(palette_df, dplyr::contains("cancer_group"))
  ) %>%
  dplyr::select(cancer_group_display, n, cancer_group_hex) %>%
  # Create wrapped with (n=X) factor column for cancer groups
  dplyr::mutate(cancer_group_display_n = stringr::str_wrap(glue::glue("{cancer_group_display} (N={n})"), 30),
                cancer_group_display_n = forcats::fct_reorder(cancer_group_display_n, n, .desc=T)) %>%
  dplyr::inner_join(results_df)

Sina/IQR of exposures across cancer groups

All samples are included in these sina plots, which show the distribution of exposures for each signature across samples in each cancer group.


exposures_sina_boxplot <- results_df %>%
  # we DO visualize unknown also, but in case...
  #dplyr::filter(signature != "Other") %>%
  ggplot2::ggplot() +

Barplots of proportions of samples that are unexposed

Notably, the rug of 0s in each distribution represents samples which are unexposed to the given signature. Its useful to get a clear sense of the proportion of samples that are totally unexposed. We do not include Other in this plot.

exposures_proportions <- results_df %>%
  # remove "other" - not useful to know if samples are unexposed to signatures that aren't even present.
  dplyr::filter(signature != "Other") %>%
  dplyr::group_by(cancer_group_display_n, cancer_group_hex, signature) %>%
  dplyr::summarize(percent_exposed = sum(exposure > 0)/dplyr::n()) %>%
  ggplot2::ggplot() + 
  ggplot2::aes(x = signature, y = percent_exposed, fill = cancer_group_hex) + 
  ggplot2::geom_col(color = "black") +
  ggplot2::facet_wrap(~cancer_group_display_n, nrow = 5) + 
  ggplot2::scale_fill_identity() +
  ggplot2::labs(x = "RefSig Signature", 
                y = "Percent of samples exposed to signature") +
  ggpubr::theme_pubr() +
  ggplot2::theme(axis.text.x = ggplot2::element_text(size = 8))

Barplot of sample exposures faceted across cancer groups

This plot shows the signature exposures for each sample. Each bar represents one sample, with fills representing the different signatures. We order plots by sample 1, and we include the unknown proportion so everything has the same height. In this case, Other specifically means mutations that were not assigned to the specific 8 CNS signatures examined, but are associated (if at all) with a different signature.


# Make a column for exposure of interest to order samples by
samples_in_order <- results_df %>%

Explore: MMR2 signature and mutation burden

Which samples have MMR ~ 1, and are these hypermutators? This analysis is discussed here.

Note that this visualization is strictly exploratory and not exported.

We do not observe that samples with high MMR2 exposure have high mutational burdens. We do see that the majority of all such samples are subtyped as HGG, H3 wildtype.

Explore: High TMB signatures

When exploring MMR2, we see that the four extremely mutated samples are not dominantly exposed to MMR2. What are these samples, and what signatures are they exposed to?

All four samples are High-grade glioma astrocytoma with subtype HGG, H3 wildtype, and two are tp53 loss while the other two are tp53 activated. All of these samples have no exposure to signatures 3, 8, or N6. Two of the samples (one tp53 loss and other tp53 activated) have no exposure to signature 19.

# Grab the IDs for the four samples
hypermut_ids <- tmb_data %>%
  dplyr::filter(tmb > 2) %>%
  dplyr::pull(Kids_First_Biospecimen_ID)


# What are their subtypes?
subtypes <- meta %>%
  dplyr::filter(Kids_First_Biospecimen_ID %in% hypermut_ids) %>%
  dplyr::select(Kids_First_Biospecimen_ID, molecular_subtype) 

# Table of merged information about these four samples:
results_df %>% 
  dplyr::filter(Kids_First_Biospecimen_ID %in% hypermut_ids) %>%
  dplyr::select(Kids_First_Biospecimen_ID, cancer_group_display, exposure, signature) %>%
  dplyr::inner_join(subtypes) %>%
  dplyr::group_by(Kids_First_Biospecimen_ID) %>%

Explore: Signature 1 presence

Is there a relationship between the presence of signature 1 in a given sample, and either i) its molecular subtype, or ii) its tumor descriptor? Because signature 1 is a normal signature, we might expect that samples without signature 1 are more progressive/relapse and/or are associated with a specific subtype. For background discussion, see here.

We see somewhat of a relationship here, but the data sets are highly imbalanced across categories (include 0 and other very low counts), so the statistics are not extremely reliable.

# Grab signature1 exposures. 
sig1_exposures <- results_df %>%
  # Since exposures sum to 1 **including unknown**, we just need sig 1's exposure
  dplyr::filter(signature == 1) %>%
  dplyr::select(Kids_First_Biospecimen_ID, 
                sig1_proportion = exposure, 
                cancer_group_display_n) %>%
  # create indicator column of absence/presence
  dplyr::mutate(sig1_present = ifelse(sig1_proportion == 0, "Absent", "Present"),
                # Present should be first level
                sig1_present = forcats::fct_relevel(sig1_present, "Present")) %>%
  # merge in tumor descriptor and subtype information
  dplyr::inner_join(
    dplyr::select(meta, Kids_First_Biospecimen_ID, tumor_descriptor, molecular_subtype)
  )
Joining, by = "Kids_First_Biospecimen_ID"

We can also explore this using the signature 1 exposure directly instead of a binary absence/presence indicator, specifically across cancer groups of interest, and then specifically within HGG, H3 wildtype subtype samples because there is (mostly) enough data to do some light comparison across groups. There is somewhat of a trend here, but sample sizes are small that its not very robust to perform robust statistics across groupings.


# This chunk should NOT run in CI. 
if (!(params$is_ci == 1)) {
   
  # Grab the tumor descriptor colors
  tumor_colors <- tumor_df$hex_codes
  names(tumor_colors) <- tumor_df$color_names
  
  # First we can display proportions and tumor desriptor, across cancer display groups
  sig1_tumor_cancergroups <- sig1_exposures %>%

    # light guiding line representing 0 exposure
    ggplot2::geom_hline(yintercept = 0, size = 0.15) +

  # We can also viz with molecular subtypes, focusing only on subtypes with decent sample sizes. For now let's say N=15.
  subtypes <- sig1_exposures %>%
    dplyr::count(molecular_subtype) %>%

    dplyr::pull(molecular_subtype)
  
  sig1_tumor_molsubs <- sig1_exposures %>%
    dplyr::filter(molecular_subtype %in% subtypes) %>%
    tidyr::drop_na(molecular_subtype) %>%
    ggplot2::ggplot() + 
    ggplot2::aes(x = tumor_descriptor, 
                 y = sig1_proportion, 
                 color = tumor_descriptor) + 
    ggplot2::geom_jitter(width = 0.2, alpha = 0.5, size = 1) + 
    # light guiding line representing 0 exposure
    ggplot2::geom_hline(yintercept = 0, size = 0.15) + 
    ggplot2::scale_color_manual(values = tumor_colors) +
    # add in mean guiding point
    ggplot2::stat_summary(color = "black", size = 0.25) + 
    ggplot2::facet_wrap(~molecular_subtype,nrow = 3) +
    ggplot2::labs(
      x = "Tumor descriptor",
      y = "Signature 1 Weight"
    ) +
    ggpubr::theme_pubr() + 
    ggplot2::theme(
      axis.text.x = ggplot2::element_text(angle = 45, hjust = 1, size = 6),
      strip.text = ggplot2::element_text(size = 6),
      legend.position = "none"
    )
  
  # Plot the plots
  print(sig1_tumor_cancergroups)
  print(sig1_tumor_molsubs)
  
  # Save the plots
  ggplot2::ggsave(signature1_tumor_cancergroups_file, sig1_tumor_cancergroups, width = 12, height = 6)
  ggplot2::ggsave(signature1_tumor_molecularsubtypes_file, sig1_tumor_molsubs, width = 12, height = 6)
